## What

Create the `IoDriver` component that bridges the reactor's event notifications with the runtime's task waker system.

## Location

`src/runtime/io_driver.rs` (existing stub, needs completion)

## Role in Architecture

```
┌──────────────┐    poll()    ┌─────────────┐
│   Reactor    │ ──────────▶  │  IoDriver   │
│(epoll/kqueue)│              │(waker slab) │
└──────────────┘              └──────┬──────┘
                                     │ wake tasks
                                     ▼
                              ┌─────────────┐
                              │  Scheduler  │
                              │(task queues)│
                              └─────────────┘
```

## Design

```rust
/// Drives I/O events from reactor to task wakers.
///
/// IoDriver owns the reactor and the token→waker slab. It is called
/// by the runtime's main loop to process I/O readiness events.
pub struct IoDriver {
    /// The platform-specific reactor
    reactor: Arc<dyn Reactor>,
    /// Slab mapping tokens to wakers
    wakers: TokenSlab,
    /// Pre-allocated events buffer
    events: Events,
    /// Statistics
    stats: IoStats,
}

pub struct IoStats {
    pub polls: u64,
    pub events_processed: u64,
    pub registrations: u64,
    pub deregistrations: u64,
}

impl IoDriver {
    /// Create a new IoDriver with the given reactor.
    pub fn new(reactor: Arc<dyn Reactor>) -> Self;

    /// Register an I/O source, returning a Registration.
    ///
    /// The provided waker will be called when the source is ready.
    pub fn register(
        &mut self,
        source: &dyn Source,
        interest: Interest,
        waker: Waker,
    ) -> io::Result<Registration>;

    /// Process pending I/O events, waking relevant tasks.
    ///
    /// - `timeout`: How long to wait for events
    /// - Returns: Number of tasks woken
    pub fn turn(&mut self, timeout: Option<Duration>) -> io::Result<usize>;

    /// Wake the driver from another thread.
    pub fn wake(&self) -> io::Result<()>;

    /// Get current statistics.
    pub fn stats(&self) -> &IoStats;
}
```

## The turn() Method

This is the core I/O processing loop:

```rust
pub fn turn(&mut self, timeout: Option<Duration>) -> io::Result<usize> {
    // 1. Poll reactor for ready events
    self.events.clear();
    let n = self.reactor.poll(&mut self.events, timeout)?;
    self.stats.polls += 1;

    // 2. For each ready event, wake the associated task
    let mut woken = 0;
    for event in self.events.iter() {
        if let Some(waker) = self.wakers.get(event.token) {
            waker.wake_by_ref();
            woken += 1;
        }
    }
    self.stats.events_processed += n as u64;

    Ok(woken)
}
```

## Integration with Runtime

The runtime's main loop calls IoDriver::turn():

```rust
// In runtime main loop
loop {
    // 1. Run ready tasks
    while let Some(task) = scheduler.pop_ready() {
        task.poll();
    }

    // 2. Process timers
    timer_wheel.advance(now);

    // 3. Wait for I/O (or next timer deadline)
    let timeout = timer_wheel.next_deadline().map(|d| d - now);
    io_driver.turn(timeout)?;
}
```

